<p>According to the Sitecore community <a title="View Rendering" href="http://sitecore-community.github.io/docs/sitecore-mvc/view-renderings/" target="_blank">documentation</a>, "a view rendering is the simplest Sitecore MVC rendering type. As with all presentation items in Sitecore, a view rendering consists of a definition item in Sitecore and a file on the file system."&nbsp;</p>
<p>By default, the view rendering&nbsp;will have access to the current page.&nbsp;The .cshtml&nbsp;view has to use the RenderingModel class as the&nbsp;default model. The view can look like this:</p>
<pre class="brush:html;auto-links:false;toolbar:false">@using Sitecore.Mvc
@using Sitecore.Mvc.Presentation
@model RenderingModel

&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;FieldValue: @Model.Item["FieldName"]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>
<p>As this approach might work for several cases, there may be other cases where a custom model is required. Also, custom models would be useful to avoid hardcoded values of the field names or processing in the .cshtml view.&nbsp;</p>
<p>So, to create a custom view rendering, follow the next steps:</p>
<p>1. Custom rendering model class</p>
<p>The custom class should implement the IRenderingModel interface.&nbsp;</p>
<pre class="brush:csharp;auto-links:false;toolbar:false">using Sitecore.Mvc.Presentation;

namespace ProjectX.Views.Renderings
{
    public class CustomRenderingModel : IRenderingModel
    {
        // Use field id instead of the name to avoid issues if it is changed.
        private readonly ID FieldId = new ID("{3BA5E416-BC8E-4CEB-9D51-7E246E1C0B73}"); 

        public Rendering Rendering { get; set; }
        public Item Item { get; set; }
        public Item PageItem { get; set; }

        public void Initialize(Rendering rendering)
        {
            Rendering = rendering;
            Item = rendering.Item;
            PageItem = PageContext.Current.Item;
        }

        public string FieldValue
        {
             get { return Item[FieldId] }
        }
    }
}</pre>
<p>2. Modify the .cshtml view to use the custom model</p>
<pre class="brush:html;auto-links:false;toolbar:false">@using Sitecore.Mvc
@using Sitecore.Mvc.Presentation
@model ProjectX.Views.Renderings.CustomRenderingModel

&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;FieldValue: @Model.FieldValue&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>
<p>3. Create a rendering model in Sitecore and assign it the Model Type value.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>4. Assign the model to the rendering</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>5. Finally, publish the model and rendering, and assign it to the presentation details&nbsp;of the item where you want to display the view.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>That's it for today.</p>
